---
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import QuoteList from '../../components/QuoteList.astro';
import { TECHNIQUES } from '../../lib/techniques';

const t = TECHNIQUES.find((x) => x.slug === 'projection-of-points')!;
---

<Prose
  title={t.title}
  description={t.description}
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Techniques', href: '/techniques/' }, { name: t.title }]}
  kicker="Technique"
  jsonLd={[{ '@type': 'Article', headline: t.title }]}
>
  <p>
    Beyond the figures themselves, the chart hides a further tool found by counting points and
    projecting the remainder around the houses. The house the count reaches gives an extra figure
    for the reading. This course uses the Part of Fortune, found from the twelve house figures, as
    its standard form of the count, and reads it as a late check on the fortune of the matter.
  </p>

  <h2>Count the points</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Add up the points of the twelve house figures, and only those twelve, not the Witnesses or the Judge.</li>
    <li>Divide the total by twelve and keep the remainder. The remainder names the house; an exact division falls in the twelfth.</li>
    <li>Mark the Part of Fortune in that house with ☼.</li>
    <li>Read the figure and the house together: both good is good, both ill is ill, and a mix is mean.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    The pseudo-Agrippa's Index is a related count. It takes all the points of the chart and projects
    the remainder from the Ascendant, and that tradition uses it as a tie-breaker when the other
    findings are equal. This course follows Cattan and counts the twelve house figures only.
  </p>

  <h2>In the sources</h2>
  <p>Agrippa calls the Index "the secret of the art":</p>
  <QuoteList topic="projection-of-points" />
  <p>
    The Golden Dawn line of the tradition keeps the same operation under the name of the
    <em>Part of Fortune</em>, sought specially in questions of money:
  </p>
  <QuoteList topic="part-of-fortune" />
</Prose>
